explanation:
For assessing MISRA rule on string.h usage you must inspect any code that could invoke standard string functions on objects or pointers touched by OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. The following symbols are needed and why:

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (prototype and implementation): The target calls this and passes token and &final_id. If this function (or code it calls) uses memcpy/memset/strcpy/etc on either the token, token->obj_id, or the osal_id_t pointer, it could cause out-of-bounds accesses. You must examine its body.

- OS_NotifyEvent (prototype and implementation): Called with token->obj_id and a NULL context. If NotifyEvent manipulates the id or context using string functions (or forwards the pointer to code that does), it could violate the rule.

- OS_object_token_t (full struct definition): The code reads token->obj_id. You need the exact type and layout of this struct and the type of obj_id to determine whether obj_id is an integer, pointer, or an object requiring string operations and whether accessing it could be unsafe.

- osal_id_t (typedef/definition): final_id and outid are of this type. Knowing whether this is an integer type, pointer, array, or struct is essential to determine if any string function could be invoked on it or if copying/writing it could overflow.

- OS_SUCCESS (macro/enum) and OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED (macro/enum): These control the branch that selects final_id. Knowing their values is needed for full control-flow reasoning (which branch is taken) and to understand any special sentinel values that might affect downstream string operations.

- OS_EVENT_RESOURCE_CREATED (macro/enum): The event constant passed to OS_NotifyEvent; required to locate the correct handling path inside NotifyEvent implementation which may invoke string functions depending on event type.

- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken (prototype/implementation): This function is called by OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (per call graph). It must be inspected because it may perform operations (including string.h functions) on token or object identifiers.

- OS_Lock_Global and OS_Unlock_Global (prototypes/implementations): Also called by OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish. While locks themselves typically do not use string functions, their implementations or interactions may call utilities that do; including them ensures a complete analysis of the transaction finish path.

In short: include the full prototypes/implementations of the two direct callees and the definitions of types/constants used by the target, and include the implementations of functions those callees invoke (as listed) so you can identify any uses of memcpy/memset/strcpy/etc that operate on pointers/objects originating from OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew.
